00:33:53.750 --> 00:33:56.170
or Spock was half
of [INAUDIBLE],,

00:33:56.170 --> 00:33:58.400
so it's kind of the
same role, where this is

00:33:58.400 --> 00:34:00.650
totally logical and rational.

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:04.520
But in reality,
somebody who is total--

00:34:04.520 --> 00:34:07.550
or a thing that is totally
rational or logical

00:34:07.550 --> 00:34:10.080
is never going to
solve anything or do--

00:34:10.080 --> 00:34:13.010
I mean, first of all
they won't even get

00:34:13.010 --> 00:34:16.210
started because if something
is rational and logical,

00:34:16.210 --> 00:34:18.021
it usually needs to be
told to do something

00:34:18.021 --> 00:34:19.229
and then it can do that task.

00:34:19.229 --> 00:34:24.170
But something that
is bottom up thinking

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:26.351
or has emotional
content, which is

00:34:26.351 --> 00:34:28.100
why you have a reward
center in your brain

00:34:28.100 --> 00:34:30.725
and you have emotions, is to get
you to realize that you should

00:34:30.725 --> 00:34:32.389
even start doing something.

00:34:32.389 --> 00:34:36.267
So in reality, if Data
was purely a computer,

00:34:36.267 --> 00:34:38.350
it would sit there and
wait to be given a problem,

00:34:38.350 --> 00:34:40.559
and then he would answer it.

00:34:40.559 --> 00:34:41.400
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:34:41.400 --> 00:34:45.860
I think that plays in a little
bit to some of the other topics

00:34:45.860 --> 00:34:48.860
you talk about-- when you
mentioned choice overload,

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:49.580
for example.

00:34:49.580 --> 00:34:51.870
What is choice overload?

00:34:51.870 --> 00:34:55.020
LEONARD MLODINOW: Well,
so in today's society,

00:34:55.020 --> 00:34:59.690
we have a lot of
options for everything.

00:34:59.690 --> 00:35:02.200
You go to the grocery store,
and there's 40 different kinds

00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:05.390
of ketchup or cereal.

00:35:05.390 --> 00:35:10.490
One researcher I talked
about did a survey, reported

00:35:10.490 --> 00:35:13.610
how many of each different
products were in the grocery

00:35:13.610 --> 00:35:17.550
store, and it was bad.

00:35:17.550 --> 00:35:19.250
And these are the
kinds of things

00:35:19.250 --> 00:35:22.790
that can exhaust your brain
and get you on these loops that

00:35:22.790 --> 00:35:24.250
are not productive.

00:35:24.250 --> 00:35:28.237
And what psychologists have
found was that there's--

00:35:28.237 --> 00:35:30.820
I don't want to say two kinds
of people, because that's always

00:35:30.820 --> 00:35:32.025
[INAUDIBLE].

00:35:32.025 --> 00:35:35.240
But there's two ends of a
one-dimensional spectrum.

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:38.420
And one end, they
call them maximizers.

00:35:38.420 --> 00:35:40.060
These are miserable people--

00:35:40.060 --> 00:35:42.260
I'm often one of them--

00:35:42.260 --> 00:35:44.705
who want to optimize
and maximize the utility

00:35:44.705 --> 00:35:46.910
and economics of everything.

00:35:46.910 --> 00:35:50.600
So when I'm presented with 40
different kinds of mayonnaise,

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:54.260
I will spend an hour
analyzing each one

00:35:54.260 --> 00:35:56.210
and trying to figure
out which one is better

00:35:56.210 --> 00:35:59.660
than the other one, even
though it really doesn't matter

00:35:59.660 --> 00:36:02.070
or doesn't matter much.

00:36:02.070 --> 00:36:03.752
At the other end
are the satisficers,

00:36:03.752 --> 00:36:05.210
they call them,
who as soon as they

00:36:05.210 --> 00:36:08.762
find the first one that works,
take that one and they go

00:36:08.762 --> 00:36:10.500
along very happily.

00:36:10.500 --> 00:36:16.130
So that's what I recommend.

00:36:16.130 --> 00:36:17.950
Well, let's think
about that again.

00:36:17.950 --> 00:36:21.350
Is that really the best answer?

00:36:21.350 --> 00:36:23.390
SPEAKER: I find it
interesting when

00:36:23.390 --> 00:36:25.460
you were talking about
the creative thinking

00:36:25.460 --> 00:36:28.250
and you related
to schizophrenic--

00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:30.350
schizotypic personality traits.

00:36:30.350 --> 00:36:32.850
How are those two intertwined?

00:36:32.850 --> 00:36:35.200
LEONARD MLODINOW: So--
people pronounce it

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:40.160
both schizotypies, or
schizo-tip-ees, is a trait that

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:42.429
is related to schizophrenia.

00:36:42.429 --> 00:36:43.970
So again, if you
think of a spectrum,

00:36:43.970 --> 00:36:46.190
there would be people
who are far to one

00:36:46.190 --> 00:36:48.240
end are schizophrenic,
and then there

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:50.090
are people with
different traits,

00:36:50.090 --> 00:36:52.050
different degrees of that.

00:36:52.050 --> 00:36:56.560
And that has to do with how
attached you are to reality,

00:36:56.560 --> 00:37:00.360
and do you have a tendency
toward odd and magical

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:00.860
thinking?

00:37:00.860 --> 00:37:02.160
So based on what
I've said so far,

00:37:02.160 --> 00:37:03.701
you can imagine
that this has to do

00:37:03.701 --> 00:37:06.980
with some of the filters in your
brain and to getting new ideas.

00:37:06.980 --> 00:37:09.290
So people who are near
the schizophrenic side

00:37:09.290 --> 00:37:11.240
can often be extremely creative.

00:37:11.240 --> 00:37:13.780
Well, it's not very
creative but extremely good

00:37:13.780 --> 00:37:16.160
at idea generation
and generating

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:18.860
novel, divergent ideas.

00:37:18.860 --> 00:37:21.770
They're not really often very
creative, because that also

00:37:21.770 --> 00:37:24.290
takes some analytical thinking
to channel and figure out

00:37:24.290 --> 00:37:26.580
what you need and put
everything together.

00:37:26.580 --> 00:37:29.080
So this is an interesting trait
to look at, because in a way

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:30.784
it's a measure of your filters.

00:37:30.784 --> 00:37:32.200
And when your
filters are too low,

00:37:32.200 --> 00:37:33.830
then you're detached
from reality.

00:37:33.830 --> 00:37:35.610
But if your filters
are too high,

00:37:35.610 --> 00:37:38.600
then you're so conventional that
you'll never have a new idea.

00:37:38.600 --> 00:37:42.330
And that still has
its place more so

00:37:42.330 --> 00:37:44.650
than the other side in society.

00:37:44.650 --> 00:37:47.930
But it's a very important
aspect of elastic thinking.

00:37:47.930 --> 00:37:50.310
SPEAKER: Yeah, it struck
