00:38:24.860 --> 00:38:28.040
that I wouldn't get
if I just did work.

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:31.970
Are there other ways that
you have seen that work

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:35.960
to help people get this more
creative aspect of themselves

00:38:35.960 --> 00:38:39.952
or train their brain to
be more elastic thinking?

00:38:39.952 --> 00:38:40.910
LEONARD MLODINOW: Yeah.

00:38:40.910 --> 00:38:42.970
So I talk about different
things you can do.

00:38:42.970 --> 00:38:48.650
One is meditation and often
meditation related exercises

00:38:48.650 --> 00:38:50.150
that make you more mindful.

00:38:50.150 --> 00:38:53.180
So one of important things
to be is mindful and how

00:38:53.180 --> 00:38:55.010
are you attacking a problem.

00:38:55.010 --> 00:38:56.510
And when you're
getting to a barrier

00:38:56.510 --> 00:39:00.680
and when it's good to stop
and take another approach

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:04.640
and to be mindful of yourself
and to know what it is that you

00:39:04.640 --> 00:39:07.471
do that can help do that.

00:39:10.060 --> 00:39:13.380
Another thing is, it's
very important to overcome

00:39:13.380 --> 00:39:14.460
the fear of failure.

00:39:14.460 --> 00:39:17.355
I don't know how Google is
about that, but some companies,

00:39:17.355 --> 00:39:19.510
if you screw up, they--

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:22.200
whatever, bad review
or your project

00:39:22.200 --> 00:39:24.570
failed or you did
something that didn't work

00:39:24.570 --> 00:39:29.520
and you get criticized
for it, and they

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:33.166
make you afraid to
fail, which is a very--

00:39:33.166 --> 00:39:36.360
it's a creativity killer.

00:39:36.360 --> 00:39:39.320
As a theoretical physicist,
I know that almost every idea

00:39:39.320 --> 00:39:40.410
I have sucks.

00:39:40.410 --> 00:39:42.230
And sometimes the
only question is,

00:39:42.230 --> 00:39:44.490
does it take me five
minutes or 50 days

00:39:44.490 --> 00:39:45.770
to figure out that it sucks?

00:39:45.770 --> 00:39:47.800
And then you go
through a lot of those

00:39:47.800 --> 00:39:49.800
and eventually you get
one that doesn't, and you

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:50.860
publish something.

00:39:50.860 --> 00:39:54.749
But if you're afraid
to make that jump--

00:39:54.749 --> 00:39:56.540
or even when I'm writing
it's the same way.

00:39:56.540 --> 00:39:58.700
I write a lot of
stuff that's stupid.

00:39:58.700 --> 00:40:01.500
And I just hope that I notice
that before I publish the book

00:40:01.500 --> 00:40:03.429
and take it out and
somebody tells me.

00:40:03.429 --> 00:40:05.720
But if I was afraid to write
something that was stupid,

00:40:05.720 --> 00:40:07.500
I would never write anything
that was interesting either.

00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:08.910
I would just write a textbook.

00:40:08.910 --> 00:40:12.090
So I think that's another thing.

00:40:12.090 --> 00:40:14.350
Work on your fear of failure.

00:40:14.350 --> 00:40:16.660
And if you have a
problem, I think

00:40:16.660 --> 00:40:18.910
it's very important to fail,
talk about when you fail,

00:40:18.910 --> 00:40:23.090
think about when you fail, think
about when other people fail,

00:40:23.090 --> 00:40:24.590
open up about it
and get used to it.

00:40:24.590 --> 00:40:26.006
Like, when I learned
how to ski, I

00:40:26.006 --> 00:40:28.467
realized soon that
the first thing

00:40:28.467 --> 00:40:30.050
I would do when I
got to the ski slope

00:40:30.050 --> 00:40:33.170
is fall over because I was
skiing really stiff because I

00:40:33.170 --> 00:40:34.350
didn't want to fall over.

00:40:34.350 --> 00:40:37.790
And I was skiing badly
because I was afraid to fall.

00:40:37.790 --> 00:40:39.540
But if I fall immediately,
I get that over

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:40.580
with, oh, it's not so bad.

00:40:40.580 --> 00:40:41.196
I'm going to fall today.

00:40:41.196 --> 00:40:43.050
I'm not Going to
have a fall-free day.

00:40:43.050 --> 00:40:44.220
And then I could really ski.

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:45.610
And it's the same
thing with failure.

00:40:45.610 --> 00:40:46.560
So it's good to fail.

00:40:46.560 --> 00:40:48.580
Get used to it,
embrace it, enjoy it.

00:40:48.580 --> 00:40:50.580
The more you fail, the
more success you'll have.

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:51.670
Just keep doing it.

00:40:51.670 --> 00:40:54.870
Or the more--
consistently speaking.

00:40:54.870 --> 00:40:58.230
I'm not saying that
failure is a success.

00:40:58.230 --> 00:41:02.550
So that's another
thing you can do.

00:41:02.550 --> 00:41:03.770
Oh.

00:41:03.770 --> 00:41:05.670
Argue with people.

00:41:05.670 --> 00:41:07.560
Arguing is very good.

00:41:07.560 --> 00:41:09.900
Talk to people who
totally disagree with you,

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:11.860
who are very different.

00:41:11.860 --> 00:41:14.010
If you're a very
conventional eater,

00:41:14.010 --> 00:41:15.840
go to the weirdest
restaurant you can.

00:41:15.840 --> 00:41:17.990
Travel-- I mean, all these
things, they've shown,

00:41:17.990 --> 00:41:20.151
have increased your
elastic thinking.

00:41:20.151 --> 00:41:22.400
They've even shown-- it was
an interesting experiment.

00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:28.110
They had people in a room, and
they had these paint chips.

00:41:28.110 --> 00:41:31.250
And some were red, some were
green, and some were blue.

00:41:31.250 --> 00:41:32.900
And they'd have 10
people in the room.

00:41:32.900 --> 00:41:36.480
One of them was a confederate,
an associate of the researcher,

00:41:36.480 --> 00:41:39.220
because if you're
ever in a experiment,

00:41:39.220 --> 00:41:41.232
you'll know that it's
never what they tell you.

00:41:41.232 --> 00:41:42.940
And everyone says, is
this green or blue.

00:41:42.940 --> 00:41:44.600
And they say, blue, blue, blue.

00:41:44.600 --> 00:41:46.360
And then this
confederate said, green.

00:41:46.360 --> 00:41:50.140
The thing was obviously
blue, but he would say green.

00:41:50.140 --> 00:41:51.140
That was the experiment.

00:41:51.140 --> 00:41:54.630
So then they told
people, you're going

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:56.880
to be in an
unrelated experiment.

00:41:56.880 --> 00:42:00.614
Well, if a psychologist
ever tells you that, no.

00:42:00.614 --> 00:42:04.182
Just laugh in their face.

00:42:04.182 --> 00:42:06.140
So the second experiment,
supposedly unrelated,

00:42:06.140 --> 00:42:09.930
was they'd give you these
paint chips to categorize.

00:42:09.930 --> 00:42:12.570
Now, they're all on the
spectrum between blue and green.

00:42:12.570 --> 00:42:17.222
So there's a continuous
spectrum of frequency

00:42:17.222 --> 00:42:19.680
between blue and green, and
they would give you these paint

00:42:19.680 --> 00:42:21.950
chips and you had to say which
are blue and which are green.

00:42:21.950 --> 00:42:22.658
Well, guess what.

00:42:22.658 --> 00:42:25.620
Even though the
people who saw the guy

00:42:25.620 --> 00:42:28.270
in that other
experiment, he called--

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:31.141
whatever I said, he called
the blue chip green--

00:42:31.141 --> 00:42:33.390
and they thought that was
stupid, it was really blue--

00:42:33.390 --> 00:42:36.010
when they are now
categorizing these chips,

00:42:36.010 --> 00:42:37.980
it all depends on
where you draw the line

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:39.570
between green and blue.

00:42:39.570 --> 00:42:43.630
Well, the ones who saw that guy
who said that green was blue

00:42:43.630 --> 00:42:45.490
drew the line much
closer to blue--

00:42:45.490 --> 00:42:48.070
I mean made the blue
section much bigger

00:42:48.070 --> 00:42:50.470
than the ones who
weren't in that.

00:42:50.470 --> 00:42:52.812
So even though this person's
ridiculous statement

00:42:52.812 --> 00:42:54.270
didn't seem to
influence them, they

00:42:54.270 --> 00:42:57.342
were influenced subtly
later on in their judgment.

00:42:57.342 --> 00:42:58.800
So even when someone
says something

00:42:58.800 --> 00:43:00.550
that you totally
disagree with and you go,

00:43:00.550 --> 00:43:02.255
that's really stupid,
it can actually

00:43:02.255 --> 00:43:03.630
have an effect on
your thinking--

00:43:03.630 --> 00:43:04.690
but I mean a positive effect.

00:43:04.690 --> 00:43:07.106
It can expand your thinking
and the kinds of possibilities

00:43:07.106 --> 00:43:09.000
that you think about.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.130
So yeah.

00:43:11.130 --> 00:43:16.246
We'll have some more of
this raspberry juice.

00:43:16.246 --> 00:43:18.780
SPEAKER: Now I have
that in my head.

00:43:18.780 --> 00:43:21.745
LEONARD MLODINOW:
You're right, it's head.

00:43:21.745 --> 00:43:23.370
SPEAKER: Well, we'll
